To find the photon energy \(E\) for  
\[
f = 5\times10^{18}\,\text{Hz}
\]
we use  
1) \(E_{\rm J}=h\,f\) with \(h=6.626\times10^{-34}\,\mathrm{J\cdot s}\)  
2) then convert joules to eV via \(1\,\mathrm{eV}=1.602\times10^{-19}\,\mathrm{J}\).  

— In joules:  
\[
E_{\rm J}
=6.626\times10^{-34}\,\mathrm{J\cdot s}\;\times\;5\times10^{18}\,\mathrm{Hz}
=3.313\times10^{-15}\,\mathrm{J}
\]

— In electron-volts:  
\[
E_{\rm eV}
=\frac{3.313\times10^{-15}\,\mathrm{J}}
{1.602\times10^{-19}\,\mathrm{J/eV}}
\approx2.07\times10^{4}\,\mathrm{eV}
=20.7\,\text{keV}
\]

So an X-ray photon at \(5\times10^{18}\) Hz carries about **3.3×10⁻¹⁵ J** or **20.7 keV** of energy.

